## Description Best Practices

- **summary**: Imperative, one line, no period. E.g. `"List draft BPMNs"`, `"Delete form template"`.
- **description**:
  - First sentence: what the endpoint does and main outcome.
  - Next: auth requirement, idempotency, pagination, or special query behavior.
  - Use markdown sparingly: **bold** for key terms, `code` for field names. Use `\n\n` for paragraphs if needed.
- For complex or domain-specific endpoints (e.g. advance search), include a short bullet list of mappings or options (e.g. ticket_number → business key) so the doc stays the single source of truth.

---

## Request Body and Query Documentation

- **Query parameters**: Use `Query(..., description="...")` so parameter purpose and constraints appear in OpenAPI.
- **Path parameters**: Document in the route `description` or in a docstring if the path is complex.
- **Request body**: Use Pydantic models; add `Field(description="...")` for important fields. For a representative sample, add a request body example in the route (e.g. `body={"name": "Example", "type": "default"}`) or on the schema.

---

## Operation ID and Consistency

- FastAPI derives **operationId** from the function name. Use clear, consistent names (e.g. `get_draft`, `list_drafts`, `create_resource`, `delete_resource`) so generated clients have readable method names.
- Keep naming consistent across similar endpoints (e.g. all “get by id” handlers named `get_<resource>`).

---

## Checklist Before Merging API Changes

- [ ] Every endpoint has `summary` and `description`.
- [ ] Primary success status has `status_code` and `response_model` (except 204).
- [ ] All returned status codes (4xx, 5xx) are listed in `responses` with a short description.
- [ ] Error examples use the standard `error.message`, `error.type`, `error.details` shape; no secrets or PII.
- [ ] Prefer DRY response docs: use reusable response dicts (Option A) or a Pydantic error model (Option B) instead of large inline `responses` blocks where possible.
- [ ] Tags are set so Swagger groups endpoints logically.
- [ ] Non-trivial success responses have an example where it helps consumers.
- [ ] Deprecated endpoints have `deprecated=True` and migration note in description.
- [ ] Request query/body parameters that need explanation have `description` (Query/Field).

---

## Redo / Keeping Docs in Sync

- When changing response shape or status codes, update the route decorator (`response_model`, `responses`, examples) in the same commit.
- When adding a new exception type that is raised from an endpoint, add the corresponding status code and example to `responses`.
- Treat OpenAPI as the contract: if the docs say 404 with a certain `details` shape, the exception handler must produce that shape (see `fastapi-error-handling.mdc`).
- Run the app and open `/docs` (Swagger UI) to spot missing or wrong descriptions and examples.
